# Bringing up OED

* The OED application is composed of two components, a web app and a postgresql database, each with their own docker container: oed-web and oed-database. 

* After cloning a version of OED from GitHub to a directory on your host computer, you’ll be able to bring up OED through a terminal from the local OED-directory with the command ‘docker compose up’. Unless otherwise specified in this document, the OED-directory is OED-backend. Therefore, the docker containers will be named oed-backend-web and oed-backend-database.

* You can then run a series of OED tests to validate the build from the oed-backend-web container shell (terminal within the container) using ‘npm run test’.

* Test data can be generated from the oed-backend-web container shell using ‘npm run testData’. This is usually the first step after bringing up a new OED instance for the first time.

* You’ll be able to access the OED GUI from a web browser at [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000).

* To login as administrator, from GUI goto Options \> Login \> username: test, password: password
